\begin_layout Enumerate
(Derivation 1.10) Prove that the Lagrange equations are invariant under point-lik
e transformations.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Solution.
 Let's suppose that we have a set of generalized coordinates given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q_{i}\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, therefore, we know that for this set of coordinates, the Euler-Lagrange
 equations are valid, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q_{i}}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial q_{i}}=0.
\]

\end_inset

But now, let's suppose that we have another set of generalized coordinates
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{s_{i}\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, and even more, let's assume that we have the following relationship between
 the generalized coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{i}=q_{i}\left(\{s_{i}\},t\right),\forall i.
\]

\end_inset

Now, let's prove that for this new set of generalized coordinates the Euler-Lagr
ange equations are also valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's begin by noticing the following 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dq_{i}=\sum_{j}\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial s_{j}}ds_{i}+\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial t}dt,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{dq_{i}}{dt}=\sum_{j}\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial s_{j}}\frac{ds_{i}}{dt}+\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial t},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\dot{q}_{i}=\sum_{j}\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial s_{j}}\dot{s}_{i}+\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial t}.
\]

\end_inset

Now we must remember that the Lagrangian its a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i},\dot{q}_{i},t$
\end_inset

, and with this, let's perform the following the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\sum_{j}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial q_{j}}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}+\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\frac{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}\neq q_{j}(\dot{s}_{i})$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}$
\end_inset

 therefore, the previous expression transforms into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\sum_{j}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}},
\]

\end_inset

now, taking the time derivative of the previous equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\sum_{j}\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}\right)=\sum_{j}\left(\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\right)\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}+\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\left(\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 follows Euler-Lagrange equation, we have that we can express the previous
 equation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\sum_{j}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial q_{i}}\right)\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}+\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\left(\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

And now, let's calculate the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}$
\end_inset

, thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}=\sum_{k}\frac{\partial}{\partial q_{k}}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}+\frac{\partial^{2}q_{j}}{\partial t\partial s_{i}}=\sum_{k}\frac{\partial}{\partial s_{i}}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial q_{k}}+\frac{\partial^{2}q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}\partial t},
\]

\end_inset

in the previous expression I've been changed the order of the partial derivative
s, then, following with the calculation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}=\frac{\partial}{\partial s_{i}}\left(\sum_{k}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial q_{k}}+\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial\partial t}\right)=\frac{\partial\dot{q}_{k}}{\partial s_{i}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}=\frac{\partial\dot{q}_{k}}{\partial s_{i}},
\]

\end_inset

then, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\sum_{j}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial q_{i}}\frac{\partial q_{j}}{\partial s_{i}}+\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{q}_{j}}\frac{\partial\dot{q}_{k}}{\partial s_{i}}=\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial s_{i}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}_{i}}=\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial s_{i}},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, we end with the Euler-Lagrange equations for the new system of
 generalized coordinates.
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(Problem 1.14) Two points of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are joined by a rigid weightless rod of lenght 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, the center of which is constrain to move on a circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Express the kinetic energy in generalized coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, we are going to use the help of the following diagram:
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Problem114.png
	scale 15
	rotateOrigin center

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

And from the figure, it follows that we're analizing the movement in 3D.
 But firts, let's focus on the view from above, wich corresponds to the
 a) part in the previous figure, and from that it follows that the movement
 of each one of the masses in the rod is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}=a\cos\alpha+\frac{l}{2}\cos\beta,y_{1}=a\sin\alpha+\frac{l}{2}\sin\beta,
\]

\end_inset

and, for the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 we havesomething very similar
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}=a\cos\alpha-\frac{l}{2}\cos\beta,y_{2}=a\sin\alpha-\frac{l}{2}\sin\beta,
\]

\end_inset

and from the b) view, we can see that the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 component for both masses as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{1}=\frac{l}{2}\sin\gamma,z_{2}=-\frac{l}{2}\sin\gamma.
\]

\end_inset

We also know that the kinetic energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(\dot{x}_{1}^{2}+\dot{y_{1}}^{2}+\dot{z_{1}}^{2}\right)+\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(\dot{x}_{2}^{2}+\dot{y}_{2}^{2}+\dot{z}_{2}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

so, let's calculate the derivatives.
 Let's start with the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x_{1}}=-a\sin\alpha\dot{\alpha}-\frac{l}{2}\sin\beta\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x_{1}}^{2}=a^{2}\sin^{2}\alpha\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\beta\dot{\beta}^{2}+la\sin\alpha\sin\beta\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{y_{1}}=a\cos\alpha\dot{\alpha}+\frac{l}{2}\cos\beta\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{y_{1}}^{2}=a^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\beta\dot{\beta}^{2}+la\cos\alpha\cos\beta\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{z_{1}}=\frac{l}{2}\cos\gamma\dot{\gamma},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{z_{1}}^{2}=\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

then, the energy for this particle will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{1}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}\left(\sin^{2}\alpha+\cos^{2}\alpha\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta}^{2}\left(\sin^{2}\beta+\cos^{2}\beta\right)+la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\left(\sin\alpha\sin\beta+\cos\alpha\cos\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos^{2}a+\sin^{2}b=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos a\cos b+\sin a\sin b=\cos\left(a-b\right)$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies T_{1}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta}^{2}+la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\cos\left(\alpha-\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now, let's move to the calculations for the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 particle 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}_{2}=-a\sin\alpha\dot{\alpha}+\frac{l}{2}\sin\beta\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x}_{2}^{2}=a^{2}\sin^{2}\alpha\dot{\alpha}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\beta\dot{\beta{}^{2}}-la\sin\alpha\sin\beta\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{y}_{2}=a\cos\alpha\dot{\alpha}-\frac{l}{2}\cos\beta\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{y}_{2}^{2}=a^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\beta\dot{\beta}^{2}-la\cos\alpha\cos\beta\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{z_{2}}=-\frac{l}{2}\cos\gamma\dot{\gamma},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{z_{2}}=\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

and then, the kinetic energy will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2}=\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}\left(\sin^{2}\alpha+\cos^{2}\alpha\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta{}^{2}}\left(\sin^{2}\beta+\cos^{2}\beta\right)-la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\left(\sin\alpha\sin\beta+\cos\alpha\cos\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and we can perform the same simplifications as for the particle 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies T_{2}=\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta{}^{2}}-la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\cos\left(\alpha-\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, the total energy will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta}^{2}+la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\cos\left(\alpha-\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta{}^{2}}-la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\cos\left(\alpha-\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

But we have that the two masses are equal, then this implies that the total
 kinetic energy will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta}^{2}+la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\cos\left(\alpha-\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\frac{1}{2}m\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta{}^{2}}-la\dot{\alpha}\dot{\beta}\cos\left(\alpha-\beta\right)+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies T=m\left(a^{2}\dot{\alpha}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\dot{\beta}^{2}+\left(\frac{l}{2}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\gamma\dot{\gamma}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(Problem 1.19) Obtain the Lagrangian equations of motion for a spherical
 pendulum, i.e., a mass point suspended by a rigid weightless rod.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For this problem we are going to use spherical coordinates as our generalized
 coordinates, with the restriction that the lenght, of the rodcan't change,
 which therefore reduces the degrees of freedom.
 Thus, we can analize the motion of the system by just looking at the two
 angles.
 Here I present a figure of the problem at hand.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Problem119.png
	scale 15
	rotateOrigin center

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Spherical pendulum.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

Now, we know that we can express the cartesian coordinates in terms of the
 spherical ones, by the following tranformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=r\sin\theta\cos\phi,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=r\sin\theta\sin\phi,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=r\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and then it's time derivatives will be, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}=r\frac{d}{dt}\left(\sin\theta\cos\phi\right)=r\left(\cos\theta\cos\phi\dot{\theta}-\sin\theta\sin\phi\dot{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x}=r\left(\cos\theta\cos\phi\dot{\theta}-\sin\theta\sin\phi\dot{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset

now, for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{y}=r\frac{d}{dt}\left(\sin\theta\sin\phi\right)=r\left(\cos\theta\sin\phi\dot{\theta}+\sin\theta\cos\phi\dot{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{y}=r\left(\cos\theta\sin\phi\dot{\theta}+\sin\theta\cos\phi\dot{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and finally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{z}=r\frac{d}{dt}\left(\cos\theta\right)=-r\sin\theta\dot{\theta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{z}=-r\sin\theta\dot{\theta}
\]

\end_inset

Now, we also know that the kinetic energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{x}^{2}+\dot{y}^{2}+\dot{z}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and usign the previous expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x},\dot{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{z}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}^{2}=r^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\theta\cos^{2}\phi\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\sin^{2}\phi\dot{\phi}^{2}-2\cos\theta\cos\phi\sin\theta\sin\phi\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{y}^{2}=r^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\theta\sin^{2}\phi\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\cos^{2}\phi\dot{\phi}^{2}+2\cos\theta\sin\phi\sin\theta\cos\phi\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{z}^{2}=r^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\theta}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

if, we now, sum the three previous equations, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}^{2}+\dot{y}^{2}+\dot{z}^{2}=r^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\theta\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\theta}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x}^{2}+\dot{y}^{2}+\dot{z}^{2}=r^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and therefore, the kinetic energy, will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}mr^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, the potential energy will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=mgz=mgr\left(1-\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset

and with this at hand, the Lagrangian will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}mr^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)+mgr\cos\theta,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in which I've drop a constant term.
 Now, we know the lenght is fixed, but to make this even clear, let's change
 the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow l$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}ml^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)+mgl\cos\theta,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and we also know that the Euler-Lagrange equation for this system are given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=0,\text{ and }\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\phi}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Then, performing the calculations, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{\theta}}\left(\frac{1}{2}ml^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)+mgl\cos\theta\right)=\frac{d}{dt}\left(ml\dot{\theta}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=ml\ddot{\theta},
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}\left(\frac{1}{2}ml^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)+mgl\cos\theta\right)=ml^{2}\sin\theta\cos\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}-mgl\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=ml^{2}\sin\theta\cos\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}-mgl\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset

then, we have the following equation of motion for the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ml\ddot{\theta}-ml^{2}\sin\theta\cos\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}+mgl\sin\theta=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

On the other hand, for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 variable, from the Lagrangian, we can see that there's no depedence on
 the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, only on the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

, therefore, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=0\implies\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=\alpha,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 a constant, but still we've to perform the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{\phi}}\left(\frac{1}{2}mr^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)+mgr\cos\theta\right)=mr^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=mr^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi},
\]

\end_inset

and finally, our equations of motion will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ml\ddot{\theta}-ml^{2}\sin\theta\cos\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}+mgl\sin\theta=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mr^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}=\alpha.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(Problem 1.20) A particle of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 moves in one dimension such that the Lagrangian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=\frac{m^{2}\dot{x}^{4}}{12}+m\dot{x}^{2}V\left(x\right)-V^{2}\left(x\right),\label{eq:Lagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is some differentiable function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Find the equation of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and describe the physical nature of the system on the basis of this equation.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets begin by writing the Euler-Lagrange equation considering only one degree
 of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial x}-\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=0,
\]

\end_inset

then, pluging the Lagrangian given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Lagrangian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial x}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(m\dot{x}^{2}V\left(x\right)-V^{2}\left(x\right)\right)=m\dot{x}^{2}\frac{dV}{dx}-2V\frac{dV}{dx},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{\partial L}{\partial x}=m\dot{x}^{2}\frac{dV}{dx}-2V\frac{dV}{dx},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{x}}\left(\frac{m^{2}\dot{x}^{4}}{12}+m\dot{x}^{2}V\right)=\frac{m^{2}\dot{x}^{3}}{3}+2m\dot{x}V,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{m^{2}\dot{x}^{3}}{3}+2m\dot{x}V\right)=m^{2}\dot{x}^{2}\ddot{x}+2m\ddot{x}V+2m\dot{x}\frac{dV}{dx}\frac{dx}{dt},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=m^{2}\dot{x}^{2}\ddot{x}+2m\dot{x}^{2}\frac{dV}{dx}+2m\ddot{x}V,
\]

\end_inset

thus, the Euler-Lagrange equation for this system it's given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{2}\dot{x}^{2}\ddot{x}+2m\dot{x}^{2}\frac{dV}{dx}+2m\ddot{x}V-m\dot{x}^{2}\frac{dV}{dx}+2V\frac{dV}{dx}=0,
\]

\end_inset

and now, let's simplify the previous expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\dot{x}^{2}\left(m\ddot{x}+2\frac{dV}{dx}-\frac{dV}{dx}\right)+\left(2m\ddot{x}V+2\frac{dV}{dx}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies m\dot{x}^{2}\left(m\ddot{x}+\frac{dV}{dx}\right)+2V\left(m\ddot{x}+\frac{dV}{dx}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left(m\dot{x}^{2}+2V\right)\left(m\ddot{x}+\frac{dV}{dx}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

but we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\frac{m}{2}\dot{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and if the system is conservative, then it follows that the force can
 be obtained via the gradient, or in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $F=-\frac{dV}{dx}$
\end_inset

, therefore, if we plug this information in the previous equation, we have
 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left(2T+2V\right)\left(m\ddot{x}-F\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\left(T+V\right)\left(m\ddot{x}-F\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(Problem 1.21) Two mass points of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 are connected by a string passing through a hole in a smooth table so that
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 rests on the table surface and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 hangs suspended.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 moves in a vertical line, what are the generalized coordinates for the
 system? Write the Lagrange equations for the system and if possible, discuss
 the physical significance any of them might have.
 Reduce the problem to a second-orer differential equation and obtain a
 first integral.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
First of all let's write a diagram of the problem, which is given in the
 following figure 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Problem121.png
	scale 25
	rotateOrigin center

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diagram of Problem 1.21.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Now, for this problem, we have one constraint, which is the lenght of the
 string, and because of this constraint the number of degrees of fredom
 will reduce.
 Moreover, because the mass falling down, respect to the table, is just
 able to move in the vertical direction, i.e., we just need one coordinate
 to describe its motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the motion of the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 we are going to use polar coordinates, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r,\theta\}$
\end_inset

, but because the masses are connected, via the following equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l=r+s,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate of the particle on the table, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate for the particle 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

falling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 down, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 the lenght os the string.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, we have the following set of generalized coordinates for the system
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{1}:\rightarrow x=\left(l-s\right)\cos\theta,\hspace{1em}y=\left(l-s\right)\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{2}:\rightarrow s=s.
\]

\end_inset

But as I mention before, the radial coordinate of the particle 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not free, instead, it's related to the coordinate for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, and therefore, we can express it in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 thus, the coordinates for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 end up being 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{1}:\rightarrow x=\left(l-s\right)\cos\theta,\hspace{1em}y=\left(l-s\right)\sin\theta.
\]

\end_inset

And even more, we know that the kinetic energy, in terms of polar coordinates
 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

therefore, for this problem we will have, for the particle 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{1}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(\dot{s}^{2}+\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

whereas, for the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, we just have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2}=\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\dot{s}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, the total kinetic energy will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=T_{1}+T_{2}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(\dot{s}^{2}+\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right)+\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\dot{s}^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore T=\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

And, for the potetial energy, we just have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=-m_{2}gs,
\]

\end_inset

thus, the Lagrangian will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=T-V,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+m_{2}gs.
\]

\end_inset

Now, we have that the Euler-Lagrange equations for this system will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial s}=0,\hspace{1em}\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=0.
\]

\end_inset

So, let's perform the calculations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+m_{2}gs\right)=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{s}}=\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\ddot{s},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial s}=\frac{\partial}{\partial s}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+m_{2}gs\right)=-m_{1}\left(l-s\right)\dot{\theta}^{2}+m_{2}g,
\]

\end_inset

thus, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\ddot{s}+m_{1}\left(l-s\right)\dot{\theta}^{2}-m_{2}g=0,\label{eq:SEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whilr for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 coordinate, we have that there is no dependence of the Lagrangian with
 respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, just with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

, therefore, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{\theta}}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+m_{2}gs\right)=\frac{d}{dt}\left(m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}=\alpha,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 it's just a constant, and this also implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\theta}=\frac{\alpha}{m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

.
 And with this information at hand, we can write the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\ddot{s}+m_{1}\left(l-s\right)\left(\frac{\alpha}{m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}}\right)^{2}-m_{2}g=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\ddot{s}+\frac{\alpha^{2}}{m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{3}}-m_{2}g=0,
\]

\end_inset

if we now multiply the previous equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{s}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\ddot{s}\dot{s}+\frac{\alpha^{2}\dot{s}}{m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{3}}-m_{2}g\dot{s}=0,
\]

\end_inset

which can be integrated
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{\alpha^{2}}{m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}}-m_{2}gs=\beta,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 it's just a constant, and moreover, if we plug the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in the previous equation, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+\frac{\left(m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}\right)^{2}}{m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}}-m_{2}gs=\beta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)\dot{s}^{2}+m_{1}\left(l-s\right)^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}-m_{2}gs=\beta,
\]

\end_inset

butm the left hand side of the previous equiation it's just the total energy,
 therefore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T+V=\beta,
\]

\end_inset

i.e., the energy is conserved.
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(Problem 1.22) Obtain the Lagrangian equations of motion for a double pendulum.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For this problem we can use the angles of the two angles as generalized
 coordinates, as shown in the figure 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Problem122.png
	scale 35
	rotateOrigin center

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diagram of Problem 1.22.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Then, we can express the cartesian coordinates of the positions of the masses
 in terms of these angles.
 So, let's do that, for the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

, let's suppose lenght 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 fixed, and for this, the motion will be described by the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, and in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}=l_{1}\sin\theta,\hspace{1em}\hspace{1em}y_{1}=-l_{1}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

whereas for the second pendulum, we're going to assume the lengh it's fixed
 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the coordinates will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}=x_{1}+l_{2}\sin\phi,\hspace{1em}\hspace{1em}y_{2}=y_{1}-l_{2}\cos\phi,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies x_{2}=l_{1}\sin\theta+l_{2}\sin\phi,\hspace{1em}\hspace{1em}y_{2}=-l_{1}\cos\theta-l_{2}\cos\phi.
\]

\end_inset

And with this at hand, we can calculate the kinetic energy for each one
 of the masses, thus, for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{1}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}\left(\dot{x}_{1}^{2}+\dot{y}_{1}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}_{1}=l_{1}\cos\theta\dot{\theta},\hspace{1em}\hspace{1em}\dot{y}_{1}=l_{1}\sin\theta\dot{\theta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x}_{1}^{2}+\dot{y}_{1}^{2}=l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

and then, the kinetic energy will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{1}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, for the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2}=\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(\dot{x}_{2}^{2}+\dot{y}_{2}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}_{2}=l_{1}\cos\theta\dot{\theta}+l_{2}\cos\phi\dot{\phi},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{y}_{2}=l_{1}\sin\theta\dot{\theta}+l_{2}\sin\phi\dot{\phi},
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}_{2}^{2}+\dot{y}_{2}^{2}=l_{1}^{2}\cos^{2}\theta\dot{\theta}^{2}+l_{2}^{2}\cos^{2}\phi\dot{\phi}^{2}+2l_{1}l_{2}\cos\theta\cos\phi\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}+l_{1}^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\theta}^{2}+l_{2}^{2}\sin^{2}\phi\dot{\phi}^{2}+2l_{1}l_{2}\sin\theta\sin\phi\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x}_{2}^{2}+\dot{y}_{2}^{2}=l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\theta+\sin^{2}\theta\right)+l_{2}^{2}\dot{\phi}^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\phi+\sin^{2}\phi\right)+2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\left(\cos\theta\cos\phi+\sin\theta\sin\phi\right),
\]

\end_inset

but we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos^{2}a+\sin^{2}b=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos a\cos b+\sin a\sin b=\cos\left(a-b\right)$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}_{2}^{2}+\dot{y}_{2}^{2}=l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+l_{2}^{2}\dot{\phi}^{2}+2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, the kinetic energy for this particle will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2}=\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+l_{2}^{2}\dot{\phi}^{2}+2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

and therefore the kinetic energy of the system will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+l_{2}^{2}\dot{\phi}^{2}+2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

And, the potential energy for the system will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=V_{1}+V_{2},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the potential energy for the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, and for each one, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{1}=m_{1}gl_{1}\left(1-\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}=m_{2}g\left[l_{1}\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+l_{2}\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

and then, the total potential will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=g\left\{ m_{1}l_{1}\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+m_{2}\left[l_{1}\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+l_{2}\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right]\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

and then, the Lagrangian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}m_{1}l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m_{2}\left(l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}+l_{2}^{2}\dot{\phi}^{2}+2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-g\left\{ m_{1}l_{1}\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+m_{2}\left[l_{1}\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+l_{2}\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right]\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

and in this case, the Euler-Lagrange equations will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\phi}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Now, let's performd the derivatives, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(m_{1}l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}+m_{2}l_{1}^{2}\dot{\theta}+2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=m_{1}l_{1}^{2}\ddot{\theta}+m_{2}l_{1}^{2}\ddot{\theta}+2l_{1}l_{2}\ddot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)-2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\phi}\left(\dot{\theta}-\dot{\phi}\right)\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)l_{1}^{2}\ddot{\theta}++2l_{1}l_{2}\ddot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)-2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\phi}\left(\dot{\theta}-\dot{\phi}\right)\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right),
\]

\end_inset

and for the other derivative we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=-l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right)-m_{1}gl_{1}\sin\theta-m_{2}gl_{2}\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=-l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right)-\left(m_{1}l_{1}+m_{2}l_{2}\right)g\sin\theta.
\]

\end_inset

Theferore, we have that the Euler-Lagrange equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(m_{1}+m_{2}\right)l_{1}^{2}\ddot{\theta}++2l_{1}l_{2}\ddot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)-2l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\phi}\left(\dot{\theta}-\dot{\phi}\right)\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right)+l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right)+\left(m_{1}l_{1}+m_{2}l_{2}\right)g\sin\theta=0.
\]

\end_inset

Now let's move on to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 coordinate, and calculate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(m_{2}l_{2}^{2}\dot{\phi}+m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=m_{2}l_{2}^{2}\ddot{\phi}+m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\ddot{\theta}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)+m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right),
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\phi}=m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)+m_{2}gl_{2}\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and finally, the Euler-Lagrange equations for the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{2}l_{2}^{2}\ddot{\phi}+m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\ddot{\theta}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)+m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\sin\left(\theta-\phi\right)-m_{2}l_{1}l_{2}\dot{\theta}\dot{\phi}\cos\left(\theta-\phi\right)-m_{2}gl_{2}\sin\theta=0.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(Problem 2.13) A heavy particle is placed at the top of a vertical hoop.
 Calculate the reaction of the hoop on the particle by means of the Lagrange's
 undetermined multipliers and Lagrande's equations.
 Find the height at which the particle falls of.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For this problem let's use polar coordinates as generalized coordinates,
 and moreover, because of the nature of the problem, we can use lagrange
 undefined multipliers, which, of course, modifiy the Euler-Lagrange equations.
 So let'a begin, by definition, the Lagrangian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=T-V,
\]

\end_inset

but in this case, as stated before, we can use polar coordinates, with the
 transformation from cartesian to polar given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=r\cos\theta,y=r\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset

with the equation above, we can find the kinetec energy as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{x}^{2}+\dot{y}^{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies T=\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

now, for the potential energy, we can see that it'll be given by the following
 expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=mgr\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

therefore, the Lagrangian will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right)-mgr\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

but, we also have the restriction giving by the fact that the particle is
 placed at the hoop, for now, let's assume that the particle is constrained
 to allways be moving on the surface of the hoop, and then the constraint,
 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g=R-r,\label{eq:ConstraintP213}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the radius of the hoop and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate of the particle.
 Now, in order to consider the constraint we have to modify the Euler-Lagrange
 equations as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{r}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial r}=\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial r},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial\theta},
\]

\end_inset

but, as we can see from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConstraintP213"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, there is no dependece on the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, therefore, the Euler-Lagrage equations simplify to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{r}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial r}=\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial r},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=0,
\]

\end_inset

now lets work with Euler Lagrange equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{r}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{r}}\left(\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right)-mgr\cos\theta\right)\right)=\frac{d}{dt}\left(m\dot{r}\right)=m\ddot{r},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{r}}=m\ddot{r},
\]

\end_inset

on the other hand, for the other derivative, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial r}=\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right)-mgr\cos\theta\right)=mr\dot{\theta}^{2}-mgcos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial r}=mr\dot{\theta}^{2}-mgcos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

therefore, the Lagrangian for the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 coodinate becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{r}-mr\dot{\theta}^{2}+mgcos\theta=\lambda,
\]

\end_inset

but because the particle is contraint to move in the surface of the hoop,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R$
\end_inset

, and also it's time derivatives would be equal to zero, therefore, we have
 that the last equation reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-mR\dot{\theta}^{2}+mgcos\theta=\lambda,\label{eq:rEquationP213}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and following the same line of though, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{\theta}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial\dot{\theta}}\left(\frac{1}{2}m\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right)-mgr\cos\theta\right)\right)=2mr\dot{r}\dot{\theta}+mr^{2}\ddot{\theta},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\theta}=mgr\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and therefore, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2mr\dot{r}\dot{\theta}+mr^{2}\ddot{\theta}-mgr\sin\theta=0,
\]

\end_inset

and as before, considering the constraint equations, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R$
\end_inset

, and also the time derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 will be equal to zero, thus, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mR^{2}\ddot{\theta}-mgR\sin\theta=0.\label{eq:OEquationP213}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, let's focus on the previous equation, and rewrite in the following
 way 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\theta}=\frac{g}{R}\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and now, let's use the chain rule to rewrite the left hand side of the above
 equation as a derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\theta}=\frac{d}{dt}\dot{\theta}=\frac{d\dot{\theta}}{d\theta}\frac{d\theta}{dt}=\frac{d\dot{\theta}}{d\theta}\dot{\theta},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\ddot{\theta}=\frac{d\dot{\theta}}{d\theta}\dot{\theta},
\]

\end_inset

and therefore, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\dot{\theta}}{d\theta}\dot{\theta}=\frac{g}{R}\sin\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{\theta}d\dot{\theta}=\frac{g}{R}\sin\theta d\theta,
\]

\end_inset

therefore, we can integrate the previous equation asuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\dot{\theta}}\dot{\theta}d\dot{\theta}=\int_{0}^{\theta}\frac{g}{R}\sin\theta d\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{\theta}^{2}=\frac{2g}{R}\left(1-\cos\theta\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now, if we insert the previous equation into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rEquationP213"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-mR\frac{2g}{R}\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+mgcos\theta=\lambda,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\lambda=-2mg+2mg\cos\theta+mgcos\theta=mg\left(3\cos\theta-2\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\therefore\lambda=mg\left(3\cos\theta-2\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and, from the previous equation we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\arccos\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, if we consider that the surface cannot hold the mass anymore at some
 angle, then the mass will fly, when the next condition becames true 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta>\arccos\frac{2}{3}\approx48^{\circ},
\]

\end_inset

and therefore the height at which the particle will fly, becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2}{3}R.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the one-dimensional power law force 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=-k|x|^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What it is the corresponding potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(x\right)?$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that the corresponding potential energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is conserved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Express the turning point of the motion 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{max}|$
\end_inset

 in terms of the maximum instantaneous velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{max}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's begin by plotting the force law for several 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ProblemMForce.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Plot of several power force law, 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

We can see that because of the nature of the force, i.e., the dependence of
 the absolute value, the force doesn't take any negative values.
 From newtonian mechanics we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overrightarrow{F}=-\nabla U,
\]

\end_inset

or, in 1D, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(x\right)=-\frac{dU}{dx},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, we can find the potential by simply taking the integral of the
 previous expresion, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=-\int Fdx.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, we also know that the definition of the absolute value
 it's given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

, therefore, we can split the previous integral in two parts, let's begin
 by considering 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=-\int\left(-k|x|^{n}\right)dx=k\int x^{n}dx=\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies U=\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C,
\]

\end_inset

it's important to notice that in the previous integration, we're only consdering
 the cases in which 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, on the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

 we can make the following change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-x$
\end_inset

, and we also need to change the domain in which we're integrating the function,
 but we will end with the same integral, therefore we have that the potential
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\frac{|x|^{n+1}}{n+1}+C.
\]

\end_inset

An even more, because we were able to write the force as the derivative
 of some potential function, we know that this implies that the system is
 conservative, i.e, the total energy is conserved.
 And finnaly, by the conservation of the energy we can choose two points
 in time, which will be one in which the potential energy is zero, and the
 energy is max, and other when the velocity iz zero, which it's the turning
 point, and the potential is max, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}mv_{max}^{2}=\frac{|x_{max}|^{n+1}}{n+1},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies|x_{max}|^{n+1}=\left(\frac{n+1}{2}\right)mv_{max}^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore|x_{max}|=\sqrt[n+1]{\left(\frac{n+1}{2}\right)mv_{max}^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_body
\end_document
